The issue is with the `Checkbox` component onClick callback, specifically with the way you handle updating the state with `setIsCheckedWhenPaymentAmount` and `handleCheckboxClicked`. 

You're updating the `isCheckedWhenPaymentAmount` in `handleCheckboxClicked`, but as these updates might be asynchronous, you should not immediately read the `isCheckedWhenPaymentAmount` right after updating it. Instead, use a callback function to set the new state based on the previous state.

Here's the fix: Update your `handleCheckboxClicked` function like this:

```javascript
const handleCheckboxClicked = (txnId: number) => {
  setIsCheckedWhenPaymentAmount((prevChecked) => !prevChecked);

  if (!isCheckedWhenPaymentAmount) {
    const value = outstandingTableLines.filter((x) => x.txnId === txnId)[0].openBalance;
    setPaymentAmount(value.toString());

    const calcAmount = Number(amount) + Number(value);
    handleAmountUpdate(calcAmount.toString());
    onPaymentFieldUpdated(txnId, {
      linkedPaymentAmount: value.toString(),
      isLinkedPaymentAmount: true,
    });
  } else {
    setPaymentAmount('');
    const value1 = outstandingTableLines.filter((x) => x.txnId === txnId)[0].isLinkedPaymentAmount;

    if (value1) {
      const value = outstandingTableLines.filter((x) => x.txnId === txnId)[0].linkedPaymentAmount;

      if (value) {
        const calcAmount = Number(amount) - Number(value);
        handleAmountUpdate(calcAmount.toString());
        onPaymentFieldUpdated(txnId, {
          linkedPaymentAmount: '',
        });
      }
    }
  }
};
```

By passing a callback function `(prevChecked) => !prevChecked` to `setIsCheckedWhenPaymentAmount`, we make sure we always update the state based on the previous state, and we don't rely on immediately reading the updated state.

